Serbiaâ€™s state-owned railway company
 Zeleznice Srbije  needs 4 billion euros ($5.7 billion) to
complete its main rail corridor and is negotiating loans with
European financial institutions,  Politika  newspaper said.  The company is discussing loans with the  European Bank For
Reconstruction and Development  and the  European Investment Bank 
to finance works on 750 kilometers (466 miles) of tracks, the
newspaper reported, citing Deputy Infrastructure Minister Dejan
Lasica as saying. The money will also cover the cost of land
expropriation. The new railroad will allow trains to move at 160
kilometers (99.4 miles) an hour.  To contact the reporter on this story:
